{
  "text": "Trimmomatic, v 0.36 [CITATION_1] was used to quality-filter the raw reads: trimming with a quality sliding window of 4:8; cropping sequences to remove 20 bases from the start and bases beyond 220 from the end (based on results of analysis by FASTQC); and filtering out sequences less than 150 bp long. Reads were processed using Kneaddata (https://bitbucket.org/bio bakery/kneaddata/wiki/Home) to remove human DNA sequences. Quality trimmed reads were processed through HUMAnN2 (http://huttenhower.sph. harvard.edu/humann2) with default settings, which includes 1) screening with MetaPhlAn2 for taxonomic identification using clade-specific markers [CITATION_2] ; 2) mapping reads to annotated pangenomes of the identified species in the ChocoPhlAn database using Bowtie2 [CITATION_3] to obtain species-specific gene lists (nucleotide search); 3) translated search of unmapped reads against UniRef90 protein reference database [CITATION_4] using DIAMOND [CITATION_5] . The generated gene lists are then collapsed into protein families and enzyme classes/pathways using PFam [CITATION_6] and MetCyc [CITATION_7] databases, respectively. Species contribution is based on results obtained in step 2 above. The resulting gene families and pathway abundance files from all samples were joined and normalized to relative abundance. Merged data were unstratified and LEfSe was employed to identify differentially abundant features, as described above.",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "7324039",
    "[CITATION_2]": "2099459",
    "[CITATION_3]": "205420407",
